very, very interesting talk.

00:46:01.100 --> 00:46:04.520
I think throughout this talk,
mostly or even completely,

00:46:04.520 --> 00:46:09.560
we've contrasted India with the
West, with the United States,

00:46:09.560 --> 00:46:10.430
specifically.

00:46:10.430 --> 00:46:17.270
And there are some ways where
we share similar problems.

00:46:17.270 --> 00:46:19.250
One obvious thing
that we did talk about

00:46:19.250 --> 00:46:22.550
was sexual content online.

00:46:22.550 --> 00:46:24.440
I think even in
the United States,

00:46:24.440 --> 00:46:26.570
the availability of
problematic content online

00:46:26.570 --> 00:46:29.980
far outpaces the availability
of good sexual education

00:46:29.980 --> 00:46:32.670
in most of this country,
just as an example.

00:46:32.670 --> 00:46:36.110
So I am wondering
what lessons have

00:46:36.110 --> 00:46:38.240
you learned from your
exploration of how

00:46:38.240 --> 00:46:42.320
India got connected that might
apply to the United States

00:46:42.320 --> 00:46:43.300
as well?

00:46:43.300 --> 00:46:46.920
RAVI AGRAWAL: Wow, so
the other way around.

00:46:46.920 --> 00:46:49.747
Wow, that's a great question.

00:46:49.747 --> 00:46:52.080
I think because India has
discovered all of these things

00:46:52.080 --> 00:46:56.910
later, it is sort of learning
from the West's mistakes

00:46:56.910 --> 00:46:58.390
as it goes along.

00:46:58.390 --> 00:47:05.880
But in terms of lessons from
India, one takeaway, I think,

00:47:05.880 --> 00:47:12.070
would be that cultures
use technology in ways

00:47:12.070 --> 00:47:14.230
that are very unique to them.

00:47:14.230 --> 00:47:20.840
And I think, especially
for investors here,

00:47:20.840 --> 00:47:24.260
you know, anyone who's dealing
with products that are global,

00:47:24.260 --> 00:47:26.750
I think it's very
important to see

00:47:26.750 --> 00:47:29.990
each culture, each
community, each country

00:47:29.990 --> 00:47:35.430
as having very unique ways
of dealing with technology.

00:47:35.430 --> 00:47:42.380
And so for example, when
I was talking about cash,

00:47:42.380 --> 00:47:46.700
India's what I like to call
a very low trust society.

00:47:46.700 --> 00:47:50.120
And that's because Indians
almost always just assume

00:47:50.120 --> 00:47:52.550
that anything that could
go wrong in the system

00:47:52.550 --> 00:47:53.900
will go wrong.

00:47:53.900 --> 00:47:55.760
Indians don't show up
for meetings on time

00:47:55.760 --> 00:47:57.510
because they don't
expect the other person

00:47:57.510 --> 00:47:59.090
to show up on time.

00:47:59.090 --> 00:48:01.220
Indians like to pay
for things in cash

00:48:01.220 --> 00:48:03.590
because they think
something could go wrong

00:48:03.590 --> 00:48:05.870
with a credit card.

00:48:05.870 --> 00:48:09.710
So cash on delivery is a
very big thing in India.

00:48:09.710 --> 00:48:12.260
Amazon's a big competitor
in India, Flipkart,

00:48:12.260 --> 00:48:16.700
began as a company that was
delivering books to people,

00:48:16.700 --> 00:48:18.590
and then those customers
would pay for it

00:48:18.590 --> 00:48:21.500
in cash at their doorsteps.

00:48:21.500 --> 00:48:23.510
And the reason why
I'm explaining this

00:48:23.510 --> 00:48:32.050
as a lesson for America
is that each market

00:48:32.050 --> 00:48:33.580
will develop in its
own way and will

00:48:33.580 --> 00:48:37.000
have its own sort of unique
relationship with how

00:48:37.000 --> 00:48:39.265
technology develops and
how it should be used.

00:48:41.820 --> 00:48:44.790
That said, I wish
I could tell you

00:48:44.790 --> 00:48:49.290
that India, for all of its
great connections with faith

00:48:49.290 --> 00:48:50.730
and religion-- you
know, India was

00:48:50.730 --> 00:48:52.410
the birthplace for religions.

00:48:52.410 --> 00:48:54.330
It was the birthplace of yoga.

00:48:54.330 --> 00:48:56.940
I wish I could tell you
that Indians have a better

00:48:56.940 --> 00:48:59.166
relationship with screens.

00:48:59.166 --> 00:48:59.790
And they don't.

00:49:03.930 --> 00:49:06.690
As a screen addiction is a
problem here in the West,

00:49:06.690 --> 00:49:08.760
it is becoming so in India.

00:49:08.760 --> 00:49:13.920
And so in that sense, India
really has no lessons to offer.

00:49:13.920 --> 00:49:17.760
And the solution to that problem
will have to be a global one.

00:49:17.760 --> 00:49:20.264
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:49:20.264 --> 00:49:23.320
AUDIENCE: Hi, Ravi, thanks
for joining us and sharing

00:49:23.320 --> 00:49:24.060
your thoughts.

00:49:24.060 --> 00:49:27.410
I wanted you to go a
little bit more into--

00:49:27.410 --> 00:49:29.890
that you briefly mentioned
regulation and regulation

00:49:29.890 --> 00:49:33.370
of technology and the foreign
was this Indian company

00:49:33.370 --> 00:49:34.390
dynamic.

00:49:34.390 --> 00:49:36.947
And I've seen many
stories recently

00:49:36.947 --> 00:49:38.530
about the government
wanting to change

00:49:38.530 --> 00:49:41.780
how things are and the status
quo, things like localization

00:49:41.780 --> 00:49:42.830
and stuff like that.

00:49:42.830 --> 00:49:44.530
So I just wanted to
hear your thoughts

00:49:44.530 --> 00:49:47.077
on how things look right
now and what you think

00:49:47.077 --> 00:49:48.160
will happen in the future?

00:49:48.160 --> 00:49:50.320
Like, is India going
to become another China

00:49:50.320 --> 00:49:52.510
in terms of foreign
companies not being

00:49:52.510 --> 00:49:55.252
able to play on the same level?

00:49:55.252 --> 00:49:56.710
RAVI AGRAWAL: I
mean, I don't think

00:49:56.710 --> 00:49:59.110
India can become
another China, and I

00:49:59.110 --> 00:50:02.910
don't think even the
government wants to do that.

00:50:02.910 --> 00:50:05.560
China is just such a different
market to begin with.

00:50:05.560 --> 00:50:09.790
Their internet is almost
like one language.

00:50:09.790 --> 00:50:12.520
They have apps that
are, as you all know,

00:50:12.520 --> 00:50:15.220
an entire ecosystem
in and of itself.

00:50:15.220 --> 00:50:17.710
India's evolution with the
internet has been so different.

00:50:17.710 --> 00:50:21.370
Number one, India has more than
200 million English language

00:50:21.370 --> 00:50:24.070
users.

00:50:24.070 --> 00:50:27.520
Right from the start, Western
companies were allowed in

00:50:27.520 --> 00:50:31.640
and became the leaders
of the Indian internet,

00:50:31.640 --> 00:50:35.230
Google being first among them,
but also Amazon, and Uber,

00:50:35.230 --> 00:50:38.740
and so many other companies
that made it big in India

00:50:38.740 --> 00:50:40.000
quite early.

00:50:40.000 --> 00:50:41.770
I think what you're
seeing now more

00:50:41.770 --> 00:50:47.560
recently in terms of regulation
is India and this government's

00:50:47.560 --> 00:50:52.000
reaction to Western
companies having

00:50:52.000 --> 00:50:54.800
such a large slice of the pie.

00:50:54.800 --> 00:50:59.020
And so for example, in
the e-commerce space,

00:50:59.020 --> 00:51:02.350
you know if the Indian
government is restricting

00:51:02.350 --> 00:51:04.780
the amount that
Western companies can

00:51:04.780 --> 00:51:07.330
own in a company or
the amount of business

00:51:07.330 --> 00:51:09.280
that they can do
in a certain space,

00:51:09.280 --> 00:51:12.760
I think they're doing that
primarily just to protect

00:51:12.760 --> 00:51:15.250
local companies from being
able to survive and stay

00:51:15.250 --> 00:51:17.000
in the game.

00:51:17.000 --> 00:51:22.420
I don't think it will ever rise
to the levels of either China

00:51:22.420 --> 00:51:26.605
or even the protectionism that
we saw in India in the '80s.

00:51:29.620 --> 00:51:33.070
I think one of the things
you must see about India

00:51:33.070 --> 00:51:38.530
is that every politician,
every regulator

00:51:38.530 --> 00:51:43.420
looks to 1991 as the year in
which the Indian economy really

00:51:43.420 --> 00:51:46.735
opened up and benefited
from opening up.

00:51:46.735 --> 00:51:50.290
I just cannot see India
going back on that.

00:51:50.290 --> 00:51:54.640
I cannot see even this
government stepping back

00:51:54.640 --> 00:51:55.430
on that front.

00:51:55.430 --> 00:51:58.090
I think they realize
that opening up

00:51:58.090 --> 00:52:00.700
is where their strength lies.

00:52:00.700 --> 00:52:03.580
I think they also realize
that the market isn't static.

00:52:03.580 --> 00:52:05.560
It's growing so
fast that there's

00:52:05.560 --> 00:52:07.506
enough space for everyone.

00:52:10.218 --> 00:52:11.570
AUDIENCE: Thanks for being here.

