00:52:58.570 --> 00:53:03.610
So coming back to education,
I talk about an Indian company

00:53:03.610 --> 00:53:05.740
in my chapter on education.

00:53:05.740 --> 00:53:08.380
It's called EkStep,
which means one step.

00:53:08.380 --> 00:53:12.910
And they have
developed, essentially--

00:53:12.910 --> 00:53:16.420
they like to think of
themselves as, for example,

00:53:16.420 --> 00:53:19.420
the Uber of primary
education, where they've

00:53:19.420 --> 00:53:22.660
created a platform where
other developers can

00:53:22.660 --> 00:53:26.590
jump in and create multilingual
content for primary schoolers

00:53:26.590 --> 00:53:30.620
or primary school teachers to be
able to use for their students.

00:53:30.620 --> 00:53:37.240
And it really is a great example
of Indian tech developers

00:53:37.240 --> 00:53:39.370
using their technologies.

00:53:39.370 --> 00:53:41.860
And this was
inspired by Aadhaar.

00:53:41.860 --> 00:53:44.620
So it's sort of an
OpenStack kind of system

00:53:44.620 --> 00:53:49.090
that allows other companies to
create other things around it.

00:53:49.090 --> 00:53:51.130
Think of Aadhaar
itself, the biometric

00:53:51.130 --> 00:53:53.500
ID system, which is Indian.

00:53:53.500 --> 00:53:55.630
It's indigenous.

00:53:55.630 --> 00:53:59.140
It's Indian run,
Indian engineers.

00:53:59.140 --> 00:54:01.090
And this was the
government's initiative,

00:54:01.090 --> 00:54:05.230
but it was led by a private
sector techie, Nandan Nilekani,

00:54:05.230 --> 00:54:07.300
for those of you
who don't know him,

00:54:07.300 --> 00:54:09.730
who found co-founded Infosys--

00:54:09.730 --> 00:54:13.150
but again, the basic
logic being that you

00:54:13.150 --> 00:54:16.780
can harness Indian
strengths and Indian workers

00:54:16.780 --> 00:54:20.350
to create these open platform
systems that could then

00:54:20.350 --> 00:54:22.990
plug into other aspects.

00:54:22.990 --> 00:54:24.800
It could plug into
the banking sector.

00:54:24.800 --> 00:54:28.430
It can plug-in to the
government subsidy schemes

00:54:28.430 --> 00:54:29.900
and so on and so forth.

00:54:29.900 --> 00:54:33.280
So I think that space is
where most of the innovation

00:54:33.280 --> 00:54:39.430
is taking place, more than
any other space, I would say.

00:54:39.430 --> 00:54:42.460
You know, if you look at
other spaces like search,

00:54:42.460 --> 00:54:45.280
or messaging, I would
argue that the most

00:54:45.280 --> 00:54:48.520
innovation is taking place in
the West or maybe in China.

00:54:48.520 --> 00:54:51.853
And India's development on
that front is more derivative.

00:54:51.853 --> 00:54:54.900
AUDIENCE: My question was
more towards the future.

00:54:54.900 --> 00:54:56.980
So if you look at
India right now,

00:54:56.980 --> 00:54:59.514
as the country is still
not fully industrialized.

00:54:59.514 --> 00:55:00.930
A large fraction
of the population

00:55:00.930 --> 00:55:07.610
is living in rural villages.

00:55:07.610 --> 00:55:10.870
[INAUDIBLE] talking about
it in the next decade

00:55:10.870 --> 00:55:13.930
or two how, say, artificial
intelligence will

00:55:13.930 --> 00:55:15.350
take your jobs.

00:55:15.350 --> 00:55:17.510
And I also assumed
that maybe instead

00:55:17.510 --> 00:55:19.810
of driving
auto-rickshaw could be

00:55:19.810 --> 00:55:22.420
as profitable as a self-driving
car for a company that

00:55:22.420 --> 00:55:23.740
wants to make it.

00:55:23.740 --> 00:55:27.054
So do you have any
thoughts about how

00:55:27.054 --> 00:55:29.595
a country like India that is so
behind in terms of technology

00:55:29.595 --> 00:55:33.050
and in terms of
industrialization

00:55:33.050 --> 00:55:35.700
would be affected, say,
20 years down the line.

00:55:35.700 --> 00:55:38.920
RAVI AGRAWAL: Yeah,
that's a great question.

00:55:38.920 --> 00:55:41.900
And I try to deal with this
a little bit in the book.

00:55:41.900 --> 00:55:43.490
So there are two
things going on.

00:55:43.490 --> 00:55:47.600
On the one hand, the
rise of smartphones

00:55:47.600 --> 00:55:50.060
will lead in the
immediate future,

00:55:50.060 --> 00:55:52.410
I think, to immense
job creation.

00:55:52.410 --> 00:55:55.250
So if you think of the
e-commerce market, which

00:55:55.250 --> 00:55:59.900
is going to grow leaps
and bounds in India,

00:55:59.900 --> 00:56:01.850
the kinds of jobs
that you create

00:56:01.850 --> 00:56:04.460
with the e-commerce
market are ideally

00:56:04.460 --> 00:56:06.650
suited to the Indian
labor profile.

00:56:06.650 --> 00:56:09.020
So you've got delivery jobs.

00:56:09.020 --> 00:56:11.790
You've got packing
jobs, warehousing jobs.

00:56:11.790 --> 00:56:13.550
Those are exactly
the kinds of jobs

00:56:13.550 --> 00:56:19.010
that rural Indian men mostly
are exactly primed for.

00:56:19.010 --> 00:56:21.431
They don't need more education.

00:56:21.431 --> 00:56:23.430
Those are the kinds of
jobs they're looking for.

00:56:23.430 --> 00:56:27.870
They're relatively well-paid
for what they're looking for.

00:56:27.870 --> 00:56:29.660
So there are enough
studies out there

00:56:29.660 --> 00:56:32.210
that show that
those kinds of jobs

00:56:32.210 --> 00:56:35.510
will create tens
of millions of jobs

00:56:35.510 --> 00:56:38.850
over the next 10, 15 years.

00:56:38.850 --> 00:56:41.000
That's sort of the
shorter-term perspective.

00:56:41.000 --> 00:56:43.310
And then there are
many other stories of--

00:56:43.310 --> 00:56:46.550
like, there's an Indian
version of LinkedIn

00:56:46.550 --> 00:56:47.780
for blue-collar workers.

00:56:47.780 --> 00:56:51.350
It's called "BabaJob," which
is then bought over by Quikr.

00:56:51.350 --> 00:56:52.790
And basically, it
sort of connects

00:56:52.790 --> 00:56:56.600
people who are seeking
a certain type of job

00:56:56.600 --> 00:56:59.000
to that particular
type of employer.

00:56:59.000 --> 00:57:03.800
You know, if you're a Domino's
Pizza in India, for example,

00:57:03.800 --> 00:57:07.100
you are looking
for a delivery man,

00:57:07.100 --> 00:57:11.110
the standards for selecting a
delivery man are pretty low.

00:57:11.110 --> 00:57:12.920
Like, if you show up
for the job interview,

00:57:12.920 --> 00:57:14.384
you're going to get the job.

00:57:14.384 --> 00:57:16.550
So the real challenge there
is connecting the secret

00:57:16.550 --> 00:57:17.810
to the employer.

00:57:17.810 --> 00:57:21.240
And technology will fix
a lot of those issues.

00:57:21.240 --> 00:57:24.680
So in the short term, I think
there's an immense benefit.

00:57:24.680 --> 00:57:27.470
The longer term is where
the troubles come around

00:57:27.470 --> 00:57:31.940
as these giant
warehouses get automated,

00:57:31.940 --> 00:57:37.280
as deliveries get automated,
as cars get automated.

00:57:37.280 --> 00:57:39.830
The thing is, it's
hard for me to imagine

00:57:39.830 --> 00:57:42.830
those things happening in
India the way I can imagine

00:57:42.830 --> 00:57:44.165
them happening in the West.

00:57:44.165 --> 00:57:49.160
See, it's one thing to
imagine a drone delivering

00:57:49.160 --> 00:57:53.360
a package to this giant
house in Pasadena,

00:57:53.360 --> 00:57:56.760
where it just drops it off
in the garden, delivery done.

00:57:56.760 --> 00:57:59.480
But can you imagine the
same drone delivering

00:57:59.480 --> 00:58:02.870
the same product to
a slum in Mumbai,

00:58:02.870 --> 00:58:06.680
where you're trying to
hover over this tiny shack,

00:58:06.680 --> 00:58:09.110
and there are, like, 200
children playing around there,

00:58:09.110 --> 00:58:11.720
and then one of them
grabs the package,

00:58:11.720 --> 00:58:14.330
someone else grabs the drone.

00:58:14.330 --> 00:58:17.840
That's the end of the
model right there.

00:58:17.840 --> 00:58:21.350
It's hard also to
imagine you know

00:58:21.350 --> 00:58:26.480
the algorithm that would work
for automated driving in India.

00:58:26.480 --> 00:58:27.890
I used to drive in India.

00:58:27.890 --> 00:58:30.390
And you're navigating
not just roads and cars,

00:58:30.390 --> 00:58:34.700
but you're navigating people,
and cows, and other animals.

00:58:34.700 --> 00:58:39.050
And it's hard to imagine
automation really

00:58:39.050 --> 00:58:42.860
working in these tiny,
narrow lanes, where

00:58:42.860 --> 00:58:47.300
it takes immense ingenuity
to scream, and shout,

00:58:47.300 --> 00:58:50.780
and corral support for
your car to get out.

00:58:50.780 --> 00:58:54.470
So on the one hand, I think
when these things eventually

00:58:54.470 --> 00:59:01.250
get automated in India, we
will see immense job losses.

00:59:01.250 --> 00:59:05.150
I just-- I can't bring myself
around to seeing that moment.

00:59:05.150 --> 00:59:06.016
I can't imagine it.

00:59:06.016 --> 00:59:07.640
I don't know if you
guys can at Google,

00:59:07.640 --> 00:59:09.641
but India's a very
different market.

00:59:09.641 --> 00:59:12.140
ARUN VENKATARAMAN: Yeah, and
it speaks to our responsibility

00:59:12.140 --> 00:59:14.840
to kind of be thoughtful about
some of those consequences

00:59:14.840 --> 00:59:16.990
before they really manifest.

00:59:16.990 --> 00:59:18.230
Our lost audience question.

00:59:18.230 --> 00:59:20.270
AUDIENCE: Hey,
thanks for coming.

00:59:20.270 --> 00:59:21.140
I have a question.

00:59:21.140 --> 00:59:25.430
You mentioned a couple of times
about the biometric ID system,

00:59:25.430 --> 00:59:28.970
but you also mentioned that
India is a low-trust society.

00:59:28.970 --> 00:59:31.820
Has there been any
worry or discussion

00:59:31.820 --> 00:59:35.150
about adopting some of what the
Chinese government is doing,

00:59:35.150 --> 00:59:36.552
using the biometric system?

00:59:36.552 --> 00:59:37.760
RAVI AGRAWAL: There has been.

00:59:37.760 --> 00:59:40.130
I think the debate has
been restricted mostly

00:59:40.130 --> 00:59:46.670
to more elite policy
circles amongst journalists

00:59:46.670 --> 00:59:48.510
and civil society.

00:59:48.510 --> 00:59:52.490
And I don't imagine that, out
of the 1.2 billion people who've

00:59:52.490 --> 00:59:54.140
signed up--

00:59:54.140 --> 00:59:56.930
I would imagine the vast
majority haven't really

00:59:56.930 --> 00:59:58.850
thought too much about privacy.

00:59:58.850 --> 01:00:01.670
And you have to think, again,
of where they're coming from.

01:00:01.670 --> 01:00:03.230
Most have come
from a place where

01:00:03.230 --> 01:00:05.750
they had no form of ID--
no driver's license,

01:00:05.750 --> 01:00:10.850
certainly no passport, no way
of getting access to government

01:00:10.850 --> 01:00:12.750
subsidies or products.

01:00:12.750 --> 01:00:15.010
So this was a big
leap, and it was

01:00:15.010 --> 01:00:17.000
a useful leap for many people.

01:00:17.000 --> 01:00:19.470
And despite being a
low-trust society,

01:00:19.470 --> 01:00:22.280
it's very telling that
they were able to invest

01:00:22.280 --> 01:00:25.550
so much trust in the government
in the hope of something

01:00:25.550 --> 01:00:28.160
better.

01:00:28.160 --> 01:00:32.010
And that speaks to the potential
for technology in India

01:00:32.010 --> 01:00:35.460
and how much hope people have
for what technology could do

01:00:35.460 --> 01:00:37.420
and how it could
better their lives.

01:00:37.420 --> 01:00:39.690
But as I was saying
earlier, there

01:00:39.690 --> 01:00:41.600
are many, many things
that could go wrong.

01:00:41.600 --> 01:00:44.790
And that is a debate
that needs to be had.

01:00:44.790 --> 01:00:47.280
It is something
that the government

01:00:47.280 --> 01:00:50.070
needs to be more open about.

01:00:50.070 --> 01:00:52.530
There certainly have
been massive leaks.

01:00:52.530 --> 01:00:56.717
And fessing up to them nice
and early and being transparent

01:00:56.717 --> 01:00:58.050
would serve the government well.

01:00:58.050 --> 01:01:00.300
I mean, everything has leaks.

01:01:00.300 --> 01:01:02.010
It's owning up to
them and dealing

01:01:02.010 --> 01:01:06.310
with them that eventually will
win people's trust, I think.

01:01:06.310 --> 01:01:08.274
So that's a longer
journey for India.

01:01:08.274 --> 01:01:08.940
Sorry, go ahead.

01:01:08.940 --> 01:01:10.440
AUDIENCE: Yeah, so
just to clarify,

01:01:10.440 --> 01:01:14.125
so overall, it's been very
beneficial, and the risks are--

01:01:14.125 --> 01:01:16.125
like, what are the more
immediate risks if not--

01:01:16.125 --> 01:01:17.208
RAVI AGRAWAL: For Aadhaar?

01:01:17.208 --> 01:01:18.366
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:01:18.366 --> 01:01:22.320
RAVI AGRAWAL: I think
the immediate risks are

01:01:22.320 --> 01:01:28.320
A, large-scale leaks;
B, the information

01:01:28.320 --> 01:01:33.240
from those leaks being
harnessed in ways that

01:01:33.240 --> 01:01:34.890
are particularly insidious.

01:01:34.890 --> 01:01:38.260
So it could be voter fraud.

01:01:38.260 --> 01:01:41.250
It could be impersonation.

01:01:41.250 --> 01:01:44.740
It could be opening
fake accounts.

01:01:44.740 --> 01:01:46.530
There's a range
of things that one

01:01:46.530 --> 01:01:52.710
could see happening based
on leaked biometric IDs.

01:01:52.710 --> 01:01:57.030
All of that said, one
advantage of this system

01:01:57.030 --> 01:02:01.250
is that A, it is a
government controlling

01:02:01.250 --> 01:02:06.740
it, not a company; and B, it
is data that is fairly dumb.

01:02:06.740 --> 01:02:09.080
I mean, it is your
ID, but it doesn't

01:02:09.080 --> 01:02:10.310
have your browsing history.

01:02:10.310 --> 01:02:13.460
It doesn't have
your preferences.

01:02:13.460 --> 01:02:16.850
It's hard to sell that
to an ad firm and see--

01:02:16.850 --> 01:02:21.560
it's not of immense value
to someone else in the way

01:02:21.560 --> 01:02:26.967
that other leaks that we've seen
from other companies could be--

01:02:26.967 --> 01:02:28.550
Facebook's leaks,
for example, through

01:02:28.550 --> 01:02:31.160
came Cambridge Analytica.

01:02:31.160 --> 01:02:34.220
So in that sense, I think
the potential for Aadhaar

01:02:34.220 --> 01:02:39.050
to be dangerous is less
so than other leaks

01:02:39.050 --> 01:02:43.340
that we now know about
from the private sector.

01:02:43.340 --> 01:02:49.160
All of that said, one
shouldn't dismiss what

01:02:49.160 --> 01:02:50.480
could go wrong with Aadhaar.

01:02:50.480 --> 01:02:54.620
And I think, again,
it's a conversation that

01:02:54.620 --> 01:02:57.996
needs to be had more openly
and robustly in India.

01:02:57.996 --> 01:02:59.995
ARUN VENKATARAMAN: Thank
you all for being here.

01:02:59.995 --> 01:03:01.328
RAVI AGRAWAL: Thank you so much.

01:03:01.328 --> 01:03:04.640
[APPLAUSE]

